'''Nagahatabe Shrine''' (ながはたべじんじゃ) is a shrine along the {{ill|lt=Kanna River (Tone River system)|Q11590491|qid=Q11590491|lt=Kanna River|1=Kanna River}} in Nagahama, {{ill|lt=Kamisato|Q1345287|qid=Q1345287|1=Kamisato, Saitama}}, {{ill|lt=Kodama District|Q938038|qid=Q938038|1=Kodama District, Saitama}}, {{ill|lt=Saitama Prefecture|Q128186|qid=Q128186|1=Saitama Prefecture}}. Its deity is {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Hatsuchio-no-Kami|Q10940642|qid=Q10940642|lt=Ame-no-Hatsuchio-no-Mikoto|1=Takehazuchi}}. It is identified with "Nagahatabe Shrine" in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} of {{ill|lt=Kami District|Q11634927|qid=Q11634927|1=Kami district}}, {{ill|lt=Musashi Province|Q907398|qid=Q907398|1=Musashi Province}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=Village Shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Origin ===
The founding year is unknown. According to shrine tradition, its origin is that immigrant-descended clans with advanced weaving techniques enshrined the weaving deity "Ame-no-Hatsuchio-no-Mikoto" as guardian deity at Nishimatoba-nishi, Aza-Miya, on the south bank of the Kanna River<ref name="Nagahatabe Shrine origin">Commemorative booklet for the 62nd Ise Grand Shrine rebuilding, ''Nagahatabe Shrine Origin''</ref>. "Nagahata" refers to a kind of silk fabric called "ashiginu," and the shrine name "Nagahatabe" indicates the artisan group "Nagahatabe clan" that wove it. Regarding the origin of that clan, the {{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|qid=Q813031|1=Kojiki}} says it descends from {{ill|lt=Kami-Ōne-no-Ō|Q119380336|qid=Q119380336|1=Kami Ōne}}, ancestor of {{ill|lt=Motosu no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11520234|qid=Q11520234|1=Motosu no Kuni no Miyatsuko}} ({{ill|lt=Minozaki no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11358204|qid=Q11358204|1=Minozaki no Kuni no Miyatsuko}}), while ''Asaue clan genealogy and estate record'' says Ame-no-Hatsuchio-no-Mikoto was the ancestral deity. Separate from the ancient native Nagahatabe clan, among the "{{ill|lt=Seven-Surname Han People|Q17211949|qid=Q17211949|1=Seven-Surname Han People}}" who came from {{ill|lt=Daifang Commandery|Q704994|qid=Q704994|1=Daifang Commandery}} on the Korean Peninsula with {{ill|lt=Achi no Omi|Q11657596|qid=Q11657596|lt=King Achi|1=Achi no Omi}} in June of {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} 4 (785) to escape warfare, there was also a clan of the "Kō" surname<ref name="Shoku Nihongi">''{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|qid=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}'', entry for June of {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} 4 (785)</ref><ref name="Shinsen Shōjiroku">'''''Shinsen Shōjiroku'', Vol. 23, lost text in entry on the Sakagami clan'''
::''In the reign of Emperor Ōjin, avoiding turmoil in the homeland, [they] came to Japan with mother, wife, children, younger brother Sensenkōtoku, and Han people of seven surnames...''
::(full quotation omitted in translation context)
</ref>.

In {{ill|lt=Ten'ei|Q1193915|qid=Q1193915|1=Ten'ei}} 1 (1110), flooding of the Kanna River washed away the shrine grounds, so it was moved from Nishimatoba of Aza-Miya to present Ōaza Nagahama<ref name="Nagahatabe Shrine origin"/>.

In June of {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 10 (1582), Kami District of Musashi became the battlefield of the "{{ill|lt=Battle of Kanna River|Q1058786|qid=Q1058786|1=Battle of Kanagawa}}" between {{ill|lt=Takigawa Kazumasu|Q953624|qid=Q953624|1=Takigawa Kazumasu}}, retainer of {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|qid=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}}, and Hōjō forces led by {{ill|lt=Hōjō Ujimasa|Q736948|qid=Q736948|1=Hōjō Ujimasa}}. War fire destroyed shrine buildings and old documents<ref name="Nagahatabe Shrine origin"/>.

In the Edo period, because the Niu deity was interpreted as earth, water, fire, metal, and wood deities, it was called "Goshonomiya"<ref name="Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō">''Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō'', Nagahama-shimogō village</ref>.

In Meiji 5, the shrine name was restored from "Nagahata Goshamiya" to the current "Nagahatabe Shrine"<ref name="Nagahatabe Shrine origin"/>.

